ions of Jewish and world literature by Sholem Aleichem, Heinrich Heine, Leo Tolstoy, Charles Dickens, and others. She published her work in the mainstream German and Jewish press, and she ran in artists’ and queer circles in Weimar Berlin and in 1930s Paris. Szalit’s fascinating life demonstrates how women artists gained access to Jewish and avant-garde movements by experimenting with different media and genres.This engaging and deeply moving biography explores the life, work, and cultural contexts of an exceptional Jewish woman artist. Complementing studies such as Michael Brenner’s The Renaissance of Jewish Culture in Weimar Germany, this book brings Rahel Szalit into the larger conversation about Jewish artists, Expressionism, and modern art.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArtistszGermanyzBerlinvBiography. 0aJewish women artistszGermanyzBerlinvBiography. 0aJews, LithuanianzGermanyzBerlinvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Artists, Architects, Photographers.2bisacsh  aBerlin art and culture.  aEarly twentieth century.  aEastern Europe.  aEuropean art history.  aExpressionism.  aGerman literature.  aGerman-Jewish.  aGraphic artist.  aHebrew literature.  aHolocaust.  aJewish Renaissance.  aJewish artist.  aLGBT / queer history.  aLithuania.  aNew Objectivity.  aPoland.  aRahel Szalit-Marcus.  aRussian Empire.  aSchool of Paris.  aWeimar Republic / Weimar Germany.  aYiddish literature.  acartoons.  adrawings.  alithographs.  apainting.  aportraits.  awoman artist.  awoman illustrator.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079776340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271098234?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271098234423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.